            },
            "answer_text": "Neither, as far as I\u2019m aware. A Byzantinist might (gladly!) correct me, but as far as I know, Eastern Rome followed the annus mundi convention for numbering years. That is to say, they dated from the (presumed) creation of the world as much as they could determine it from the Septuagint. From a quick check, the Year of Creation was reckoned at 5509 BC\u2014hence, Christ was born in 5509 e.K. and the current year 7528 e.K. (\u201ce.K.\u201d being their version of \u201cB.C.\u201d/\u201dA.D.\u201d and referring to Era of the World or \u201cetos Kosmou\u201d). ",
